#week-title("Three", "Sea Salt as Universal Fixed Magnet")

=== Core Teaching

Sea salt — sodium chloride from the ocean — represents the fixed alkali in its
most universal and accessible form. The ocean is the great collector of the
universal fixed principle: every river that flows to the sea carries dissolved
salts leached from the land, and the sea concentrates them through evaporation
over geological time. In the alchemical understanding, the salt of the sea is
the salt of the earth itself, concentrated.

Bartlett notes that salts serve as "magnets" for subtle forces, which become
available for the laboratory once the salt has been properly prepared. A sea
salt that has been purified, calcined lightly, and then exposed to the night
sky or morning dew operates as a receiver for the volatile forces carried in
atmospheric moisture — the same undetermined seed-water the student has been
working with throughout Year Two.

*The sea salt magnet experiment:* Place a small quantity of carefully purified
and lightly calcined sea salt on a clean dish. Leave it exposed outdoors
overnight, or beneath an open window during a rain shower. In the morning,
observe and record: has it absorbed moisture? Has its colour, texture, or
appearance changed? This is the mineral magnet at work — the fixed attracting
the volatile, concentrating the subtle forces carried in water.

The practical purpose of this experiment is not merely observation but
preparation: a sea salt that has been charged in this manner is a useful
substrate for later cohobation with plant or water essences. The salt's
magnetic quality draws the essence into itself and holds it more firmly than
an unconditioned mineral salt would.

*Distinguishing salt types.* Not all mineral salts are interchangeable:
- Sea salt (sodium chloride): broadly magnetic; excellent universal receiver
- Salt of tartar (potassium carbonate): strongly alkaline; more specifically
  vegetable-mineral in character due to its plant-ash origin
- Common table salt (refined, with additives): stripped of subtle qualities;
  not suitable for laboratory work
- Rock salt or halite: similar to sea salt but lacking the marine vitality;
  acceptable as a substitute

=== Topics This Week

- Sea salt as the concentrated fixed principle of the ocean
- The mineral magnet experiment: overnight exposure and observation
- Distinguishing salt types and their suitability for laboratory work
- Using a conditioned sea salt for subsequent cohobation experiments

#inner-work[
  *The Ocean and the Stillness*

  The ocean accumulates what flows to it from all directions without losing
  itself. It is the great receiving body — the fixed that holds everything
  volatile that falls into it, yet retains its essential nature.

  Sit for twenty minutes and practice being the ocean: receive whatever arises
  in awareness (thought, sensation, emotion) without being moved from the
  underlying stillness. This is the inner correlate of the sea salt's magnetic
  quality. Record what this practice reveals.
]

